- /etc/init.d/uruk flush does not flush nat nor mangle table.  This means
force-reload breaks when these tables are in use.  See comment near initd_flush.
Fix this, and accept the introduced cruft.   Tnx Wessel.

- Second prio: Make uruk init-script LSB compliant.
http://refspecs.freestandards.org/LSB_3.1.0/LSB-generic/LSB-generic/initscrcomconv.html

Supply arguments like "status" in init script, see
http://refspecs.freestandards.org/LSB_3.1.0/LSB-generic/LSB-generic/iniscrptact.html

If the status action is requested, the init script will return the following exit status codes.

0       program is running or service is OK
1       program is dead and /var/run pid file exists
2       program is dead and /var/lock lock file exists
3       program is not running
4       program or service status is unknown
5-99    reserved for future LSB use
100-149 reserved for distribution use
150-199 reserved for application use
200-254 reserved

Error and status messages should be printed with the logging functions (see
Init Script Functions) log_success_msg(), log_failure_msg() and
log_warning_msg(). Scripts may write to standard error or standard output, but
implementations need not present text written to standard error/output to the
user or do anything else with it. 

LSB required:
start   start the service
stop    stop the service
restart stop and restart the service if the service is already running, otherwise start the service
force-reload   cause the configuration to be reloaded if the service supports
        this, otherwise restart the service if it is running
status  print the current status of the service

Use example from /u/s/d/lsb-core/examples/init-skeleton.gz .

check firehol, shorewall, ferm (see nagy:/usr/local/src/debian/)

